Oh, no, I'm not a fool.

42
00:05:14,375 --> 00:05:16,791
You see, I'm at the top
of my class at the DWMA.

43
00:05:16,875 --> 00:05:18,125
I really am quite intelligent--

44
00:05:18,208 --> 00:05:19,916
[Excalibur]
Fool!

45
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:21,333
No, I'm telling you
I'm not a fool.

46
00:05:21,416 --> 00:05:24,500
My legend dates back to
the twelfth century, you see.

47
00:05:24,583 --> 00:05:25,541
[Ox] Oh...

48
00:05:25,625 --> 00:05:26,708
[Excalibur] My
legend is quite old.

49
00:05:26,791 --> 00:05:28,583
The twelfth century
was a long time ago.

50
00:05:29,125 --> 00:05:32,000
Do you want to
hear my heroic tale?

51
00:05:32,750 --> 00:05:34,083
Yes, of course I do.

52
00:05:34,166 --> 00:05:35,125
That's why I came
here in the first--

53
00:05:35,208 --> 00:05:36,875
[Excalibur]
Fool!

54
00:05:36,958 --> 00:05:39,041
[Excalibur] Now then,
if you are to be my associate,

55
00:05:39,125 --> 00:05:41,375
there are one thousand
provisions you must observe...

56
00:05:41,458 --> 00:05:44,416
You will need to peruse these
before we begin our partnership.

57
00:05:44,500 --> 00:05:46,083
[Ox] I'm sorry, but could
you tell me in what way

58
00:05:46,166 --> 00:05:47,375
I'm being a fool?

59
00:05:47,458 --> 00:05:50,208
Fool...! You have no
need for that information.

60
00:05:50,291 --> 00:05:52,041
Oh... If you say so.

61
00:05:52,125 --> 00:05:53,250
[Excalibur]
My morning always begins

62
00:05:53,333 --> 00:05:55,125
with a cup of
coffee with cream...

63
00:05:55,208 --> 00:05:56,666
Do you know why?

64
00:05:56,750 --> 00:05:57,833
Uh, no, why do they--?

65
00:05:57,916 --> 00:05:58,666
Fool!

66
00:05:58,750 --> 00:06:00,041
Listen, boy...!

67
00:06:00,125 --> 00:06:03,041
My morning begins with
a cup of coffee with cream.

68
00:06:15,041 --> 00:06:18,541
[Excalibur] Nothing beats a cup
of herbal tea in the morning.

69
00:06:19,375 --> 00:06:21,000
Thus, every morning
I begin my day with a

70
00:06:21,083 --> 00:06:23,666
cup of coffee with cream.

71
00:06:23,750 --> 00:06:25,541
[Ox] But you just said nothing
beats a cup of herbal--

72
00:06:25,625 --> 00:06:27,708
This is the first of the
one thousand provisions.

73
00:06:27,791 --> 00:06:30,875
My mornings always begin
with a cup of coffee with cream.

74
00:06:30,958 --> 00:06:32,083
Don't forget it!

75
00:06:32,166 --> 00:06:33,416
But... as I just pointed out,

76
00:06:33,500 --> 00:06:34,833
you said nothing
beats a cup of tea--

77
00:06:34,916 --> 00:06:37,833
Here... I want to
show you something.

78
00:06:37,916 --> 00:06:40,166
So these people...

79
00:06:40,250 --> 00:06:42,875
Er... are they your... family?

80
00:06:42,958 --> 00:06:44,916
The woman
standing next to you...

81
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:46,125
Don't tell me she's your--

82
00:06:46,208 --> 00:06:47,250
[Excalibur]
Of course they're my family...

83
00:06:47,333 --> 00:06:48,458
Isn't it obvious...?

84
00:06:48,541 --> 00:06:51,666
And a wonderful
family they were.

85
00:06:51,750 --> 00:06:53,375
[Ox thinks]
Past tense?

86
00:06:56,250 --> 00:06:57,375
[police sirens]

87
00:06:57,458 --> 00:06:59,041
[Excalibur]
It happened long ago...

88
00:06:59,125 --> 00:07:03,041
when I was still in
the flower of my youth.

89
00:07:04,291 --> 00:07:07,625
[uptempo beat music]

90
00:07:07,708 --> 00:07:09,625
[Excalibur]
The cities began to grow wild...

91
00:07:09,708 --> 00:07:11,208
People lost hope
for the future...

92
00:07:11,291 --> 00:07:14,250
They became lazy,
idle time-wasters.

93
00:07:17,958 --> 00:07:20,916
[yelling and fighting]

94
00:07:34,833 --> 00:07:36,583
[Excalibur]
And, to my everlasting shame...

95
00:07:36,666 --> 00:07:38,625
I was no exception.

96
00:07:43,250 --> 00:07:44,958
Someday...
I'll have enough money

97
00:07:45,041 --> 00:07:47,875
saved to leave
this city for good.

98
00:07:52,375 --> 00:07:54,750
Thus...I began to watch
the seven o'clock news

99
00:07:54,833 --> 00:07:56,791
religiously every night.

100
00:07:56,875 --> 00:07:59,708
I see...So that pretty girl I
saw in the picture was your---

101
00:07:59,791 --> 00:08:01,958
Fool...! That has
nothing to do with it!

102
00:08:02,041 --> 00:08:04,125
Uh... Then what does
it have to do with?

103
00:08:04,208 --> 00:08:04,958
Honestly...!

104
00:08:05,041 --> 00:08:06,541
You don't get it at all.

105
00:08:06,625 --> 00:08:07,875
What am I not getting?

106
00:08:07,958 --> 00:08:09,333
Number fifty-eight of the
one thousand provisions

107
00:08:09,416 --> 00:08:10,833
I would like you to observe...

108
00:08:10,916 --> 00:08:13,750
Never talk to me while I'm
humming to myself.

109
00:08:13,833 --> 00:08:15,125
This is an important provision.

110
00:08:15,208 --> 00:08:16,625
Do you understand?

111
00:08:16,708 --> 00:08:18,583
Uh, I can't help but notice
that your stories and these

112
00:08:18,666 --> 00:08:19,750
provisions don't really seem

113
00:08:19,833 --> 00:08:21,083
connected in
any significant way--

114
00:08:21,166 --> 00:08:23,333
Fool! Humming and the
nightly news share a

115
00:08:23,416 --> 00:08:26,250
very tight connection indeed!

116
00:08:26,333 --> 00:08:27,666
But... from what you
just told me about

117
00:08:27,750 --> 00:08:28,958
your past, I thought---

118
00:08:29,041 --> 00:08:31,166
A symphony cannot be
created using common sense

119
00:08:31,250 --> 00:08:32,750
and probabilities!
It is already written

120
00:08:32,833 --> 00:08:34,333
in the fate of the composer...!

121
00:08:34,416 --> 00:08:35,791
No, that's not it...

122
00:08:35,875 --> 00:08:38,708
A symphony is the inevitable
result of a bad childhood,

123
00:08:38,791 --> 00:08:40,208
deafness, and too many beans

124
00:08:40,291 --> 00:08:42,000
eaten after a
certain time of day.

125
00:08:42,083 --> 00:08:43,250
[Ox]
Obviously.

126
00:08:43,333 --> 00:08:45,458
Thus, I found myself
carrying the fate of the

127
00:08:45,541 --> 00:08:47,875
entire troupe as I performed
my dance before a

128
00:08:47,958 --> 00:08:50,083
capacity crowd
at the opera house.

129
00:08:50,166 --> 00:08:51,750
[Ox]
Wait what?

130
00:08:53,583 --> 00:08:55,166
[stage lights clicked on]

131
00:08:55,250 --> 00:08:57,250
[audience claps]

132
00:09:07,791 --> 00:09:12,750
[repetitive uptempo
jazz music plays]

133
00:09:40,458 --> 00:09:42,416
[audience oohs and awes]

134
00:10:14,500 --> 00:10:19,458
[audience applauds]

135
00:10:27,041 --> 00:10:30,291
[Black Star]
Whew! I am stuffed!

136
00:10:30,375 --> 00:10:33,250
[Tsubaki] This is nice.
I'm glad we decided to do it.

137
00:10:33,333 --> 00:10:35,458
Getting everyone together
for no other reason than to

138
00:10:35,541 --> 00:10:37,291
hang out and enjoy each
other's company.

139
00:10:37,375 --> 00:10:38,666
It's peaceful, don't you think? 

140
00:10:38,750 --> 00:10:40,125
That may hafta change.

141
00:10:40,208 --> 00:10:41,833
I can't stand out
if it's peaceful

142
00:10:41,916 --> 00:10:43,416
I'll just have to shake
things up a little,

143
00:10:43,500 --> 00:10:44,791
bring on a big ol' Black Star--

144
00:10:44,875 --> 00:10:46,416
[Liz]
Hey Tsubaki.

145
00:10:46,500 --> 00:10:47,750
[Tsubaki]
Yes... What is it? 

146
00:10:47,833 --> 00:10:49,208
Have you finished writing
that report we were

147
00:10:49,291 --> 00:10:51,333
assigned in class last week yet?

148
00:10:51,416 --> 00:10:53,458
You mean you still
haven't finished it...?

149
00:10:53,541 --> 00:10:54,750
You should hurry...

150
00:10:54,833 --> 00:10:56,416
Isn't it due tomorrow?

151
00:10:56,500 --> 00:10:57,500
Yeah, I know...

152
00:10:57,583 --> 00:11:01,250
but it is that
kind of report, so...

153
00:11:01,333 --> 00:11:03,458
Oh, it's that kind, huh?

154
00:11:03,541 --> 00:11:06,166
Do you think you could help me,
Tsubaki? Pretty please?

155
00:11:06,250 --> 00:11:07,625
[Excalibur]
Fool!

156
00:11:08,583 --> 00:11:12,416
I don't get it. I wasn't even
saying anything then.

157
00:11:22,416 --> 00:11:24,583
[Ox]
Uhh... excuse me...

158
00:11:24,666 --> 00:11:27,708
Mister Excalibur, sir?

159
00:11:27,791 --> 00:11:30,750
Mr. Excalibur, hello!

160
00:11:30,833 --> 00:11:33,041
You still alive in there?

161
00:11:33,125 --> 00:11:34,333
[Excalibur]
Fool!

162
00:11:34,416 --> 00:11:35,916
One must take time to think...!

163
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:38,208
Rushing forward without
considering things beforehand

164
00:11:38,291 --> 00:11:40,166
is the height of foolishness.

165
00:11:40,250 --> 00:11:42,208
Ah, yes, that reminds me of

166
00:11:42,291 --> 00:11:44,375
another time when
I had to consider things...

167
00:11:44,458 --> 00:11:47,750
That case was long ago,
but I remember it still.

168
00:11:47,833 --> 00:11:49,500
[bell tolls]

169
00:11:49,583 --> 00:11:51,375
[Excalibur] It was back when
I still hung my hat on

170
00:11:51,458 --> 00:11:54,500
Baker Street and
called it home.

171
00:11:55,583 --> 00:11:57,958
[Watson] Holmes have you
deduced anything yet?

172
00:11:58,041 --> 00:12:00,166
[Holmes] Of course
I have, Watson.

173
00:12:00,250 --> 00:12:01,416
It appears the perpetrator's

174
00:12:01,500 --> 00:12:03,333
depravity is equal
to his stupidity,

175
00:12:03,416 --> 00:12:04,458
based upon the elementary

176
00:12:04,541 --> 00:12:06,041
trick he has seen
fit to employ here.

177
00:12:06,125 --> 00:12:07,000
[Watson]
Elementary?!

178
00:12:07,083 --> 00:12:08,041
But we're stumped.

179
00:12:08,125 --> 00:12:09,875
The door was
locked from the inside.

180
00:12:09,958 --> 00:12:12,000
[Excalibur]
Fool!

181
00:12:12,083 --> 00:12:13,125
Precisely, Excalibur,

182
00:12:13,208 --> 00:12:14,625
couldn't have said
it better myself.

183
00:12:14,708 --> 00:12:15,958
Watson, you're indeed a fool.

184
00:12:16,041 --> 00:12:16,875
But Holmes!

185
00:12:16,958 --> 00:12:18,291
Now, Excalibur,
will you explain

186
00:12:18,375 --> 00:12:19,708
to us what you see here...?

187
00:12:19,791 --> 00:12:21,958
Use your impeccable logic
and great intelligence to

188
00:12:22,041 --> 00:12:24,041
solve the puzzle of the
locked room and point out

189
00:12:24,125 --> 00:12:26,708
the killer so we
can apprehend him.

190
00:12:26,791 --> 00:12:28,208
[Excalibur]
It's quite basic, actually.

191
00:12:28,291 --> 00:12:30,291
Perhaps the simplest
of tricks there is.

192
00:12:30,375 --> 00:12:32,208
True, it may not seem
so simple from an

193
00:12:32,291 --> 00:12:34,250
ordinary person's point of view.

194
00:12:34,333 --> 00:12:36,416
Some people may even
consider it a baffling,

195
00:12:36,500 --> 00:12:38,625
utterly perplexing problem.

196
00:12:38,708 --> 00:12:39,833
Things will often appear

197
00:12:39,916 --> 00:12:41,375
complicated
on the outside while,

198
00:12:41,458 --> 00:12:43,875
in truth, they are
simplicity itself.

199
00:12:43,958 --> 00:12:45,125
Of course, how one sees

200
00:12:45,208 --> 00:12:47,041
these things depends
on the person.

201
00:12:47,125 --> 00:12:49,583
Many people find that there
is a fine line separating the

202
00:12:49,666 --> 00:12:51,583
very complex from
the very simple.

203
00:12:51,666 --> 00:12:53,583
Okay, Excalibur,
I think we get your point.

204
00:12:53,666 --> 00:12:55,291
Could you please just
solve the case now?

205
00:12:55,375 --> 00:12:58,000
[Excalibur] Fool...!
You understand nothing.

206
00:12:58,083 --> 00:12:59,666
[Watson]  Yes,
well you're spot on there.

207
00:12:59,750 --> 00:13:00,916
Okay... I'm a fool.

208
00:13:01,000 --> 00:13:02,541
Now please explain
the perpetrator's trick.

209
00:13:02,625 --> 00:13:04,291
[Excalibur]
The trick is so elementary

210
00:13:04,375 --> 00:13:06,458
that there's no
need for an explanation.

211
00:13:06,541 --> 00:13:07,583
Ah?!

212
00:13:07,666 --> 00:13:09,250
The killer is...

213
00:13:10,166 --> 00:13:12,041
The killer is...

214
00:13:15,250 --> 00:13:15,875
--You.

215
00:13:15,958 --> 00:13:17,000
--What? Me?
--You.

216
00:13:18,125 --> 00:13:20,750
[Watson cries as he is led away]

217
00:13:20,833 --> 00:13:21,666
[Excalibur]
And thus...

218
00:13:21,750 --> 00:13:24,208
The case was brilliantly solved.

219
00:13:24,291 --> 00:13:26,208
Are you sure Watson
was really the killer?

220
00:13:26,291 --> 00:13:27,541
That seems somewhat unlikely--

221
00:13:27,625 --> 00:13:29,291
[Excalibur] To sum up, this
brings us to number

222
00:13:29,375 --> 00:13:31,458
two hundred and seventy eight
of the one thousand provisions

223
00:13:31,541 --> 00:13:32,708
you must observe...

224
00:13:32,791 --> 00:13:34,125
I hate carrots...

225
00:13:34,208 --> 00:13:36,750
never even think about
putting them in my food, get it?

226
00:13:36,833 --> 00:13:38,083
[Ox]
Yeah I hate carrots too--

227
00:13:38,166 --> 00:13:39,583
[Excalibur]
Silence!

228
00:13:39,666 --> 00:13:41,500
This is number three hundred
and forty nine of the

229
00:13:41,583 --> 00:13:42,958
one thousand provisions
you must observe...

230
00:13:43,041 --> 00:13:44,375
Meisters should eat everything,

231
00:13:44,458 --> 00:13:46,500
regardless of personal
likes and dislikes...

232
00:13:46,583 --> 00:13:50,541
Never say anything as selfish
as 'I don't like carrots' again!

233
00:13:50,625 --> 00:13:51,666
But that contradicts your--

234
00:13:51,750 --> 00:13:53,000
[Excalibur]
Do you know what kind of

235
00:13:53,083 --> 00:13:55,625
terrible tragedy such
indiscretion can lead to?

236
00:13:55,708 --> 00:13:58,833
Perhaps this anecdote will
help you understand it better.

237
00:13:58,916 --> 00:14:00,166
These events occurred just

238
00:14:00,250 --> 00:14:02,333
after my legend began
in the twelfth century...

239
00:14:02,416 --> 00:14:04,833
when I accompanied the
meister King Arthur

240
00:14:04,916 --> 00:14:07,375
on an expedition to Rome.

241
00:14:09,708 --> 00:14:11,166
[King Arthur] Facing an
army of this magnitude

242
00:14:11,250 --> 00:14:13,625
will be arduous Excalibur.

243
00:14:13,708 --> 00:14:16,166
[Excalibur] Saying such a thing
isn't like you, Arthur...

244
00:14:16,250 --> 00:14:17,875
You mustn't lose heart.

245
00:14:17,958 --> 00:14:19,583
[King Arthur]
Excalibur...

246
00:14:19,666 --> 00:14:21,916
[Excalibur] The Knights of the
Round Table never give up.

247
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:23,291
No matter what...

248
00:14:23,375 --> 00:14:25,458
You must remember that.

249
00:14:25,541 --> 00:14:27,541
You swore an oath.

250
00:14:27,625 --> 00:14:29,166
Of course you're right...

251
00:14:29,250 --> 00:14:30,541
I've forgotten myself...

252
00:14:30,625 --> 00:14:32,375
My comrades are depending on me.

253
00:14:32,458 --> 00:14:34,166
[Excalibur]
